Name: Athanasius
Description: Athanasius, 20th pope of Alexandria, is banished to Trier on the charge that he prevented a grain fleet from sailing to Constantinople.

Name: Constantinople
Description: The Sixth Ecumenical Council commences in Constantinople.

Name: Treaty of Bonn
Description: Treaty of Bonn: The Frankish kings Charles the Simple and Henry the Fowler sign a peace treaty or 'pact of friendship' (amicitia) to recognize their borders along the Rhine.

Name: Lam Sơn uprising
Description: 1426 – Lam Sơn uprising: Lam Sơn rebels emerge victorious against the Ming army in the Battle of Tốt Động – Chúc Động taking place in Đông Quan, in now Hanoi.

Name: Ensisheim meteorite
Description: 1492 – The Ensisheim meteorite, the oldest meteorite with a known date of impact, strikes the Earth in a wheat field outside the village of Ensisheim, Alsace, France.

Name: Christopher Columbus
Description: 1504 – Christopher Columbus returns from his fourth and last voyage.

Name: Elizabeth Stuart
Description: 1619 – Elizabeth Stuart is crowned Queen of Bohemia.

Name: The London Gazette
Description: 1665 – The London Gazette, the oldest surviving journal, is first published.

Name: O Ewigkeit, du Donnerwort, BWV 60
Description: 1723 – O Ewigkeit, du Donnerwort, BWV 60, a dialogue cantata by Johann Sebastian Bach for Leipzig, was first performed.

Name: John Murray
Description: 1775 – John Murray (also known as Lord Dunmore), the Royal Governor of the Colony of Virginia, starts the first mass emancipation of slaves in North America by issuing Lord Dunmore's Offer of Emancipation, which offers freedom to slaves who abandoned their colonial masters to fight with Murray and the British.

Name: Stoughton Musical Society
Description: 1786 – The oldest musical organization in the United States is founded as the Stoughton Musical Society.

Name: Tecumseh's War
Description: 1811 – Tecumseh's War: The Battle of Tippecanoe is fought near present-day Battle Ground, Indiana, United States.

Name: Alton, Illinois
Description: 1837 – In Alton, Illinois, abolitionist printer Elijah P. Lovejoy is shot dead by a mob while attempting to protect his printing shop from being destroyed a third time.

Name: American Civil War
Description: 1861 – American Civil War: Battle of Belmont: In Belmont, Missouri, Union forces led by General Ulysses S. Grant overrun a Confederate camp but are forced to retreat when Confederate reinforcements arrive.

Name: Melbourne Cup
Description: 1861   – The first Melbourne Cup horse race is held in Melbourne, Australia.

Name: cartoon
Description: 1874 – A cartoon by Thomas Nast in Harper's Weekly, is considered the first important use of an elephant as a symbol for the United States Republican Party.

Name: Mapuche uprising of 1881
Description: 1881 – Mapuche uprising of 1881: Mapuche rebels destroy the Chilean settlement of Nueva Imperial after defenders fled to the hills.

Name: Last Spike
Description: 1885 – The completion of Canada's first transcontinental railway is symbolized by the Last Spike ceremony at Craigellachie, British Columbia.

Name: Women's suffrage
Description: 1893 – Women's suffrage: Women in the U.S. state of Colorado are granted the right to vote, the second state to do so.

Name: throws two bombs in Barcelona's Liceu opera house
Description: 1893 – An anarchist throws two bombs in Barcelona's Liceu opera house, killing 20.

Name: Second Boer War
Description: 1900 – Second Boer War: The Battle of Leliefontein takes place, during which the Royal Canadian Dragoons win three Victoria Crosses.

Name: Jesús García
Description: 1907 – Jesús García saves the entire town of Nacozari de García by driving a burning train full of dynamite six kilometres (3.7 miles) away before it can explode.

Name: air freight
Description: 1910 – The first air freight shipment (from Dayton, Ohio, to Columbus, Ohio) is undertaken by the Wright brothers and department store owner Max Morehouse.

Name: Deutsche Oper Berlin
Description: 1912 – The Deutsche Opernhaus (now Deutsche Oper Berlin) opens in the Berlin neighborhood of Charlottenburg, with a production of Beethoven's Fidelio.

Name: Great Lakes Storm of 1913
Description: 1913 – The first day of the Great Lakes Storm of 1913, a massive blizzard that ultimately killed 250 and caused over $5 million (about $159,243,000 in 2024 dollars) damage. Winds reach hurricane force on this date.

Name: German
Description: 1914 – The German colony of Kiaochow Bay and its centre at Tsingtao are captured by Japanese forces.

Name: Jeannette Rankin
Description: 1916 – Jeannette Rankin is the first woman elected to the United States Congress.

Name: Woodrow Wilson
Description: 1916   – Woodrow Wilson is reelected as President of the United States.

Name: Boston Elevated Railway Company's
Description: 1916   – Boston Elevated Railway Company's streetcar No. 393 smashes through the warning gates of the open Summer Street drawbridge in Boston, Massachusetts, plunging into the frigid waters of Fort Point Channel, killing 46 people.

Name: October Revolution
Description: 1917 – The October Revolution, which gets its name from the Julian calendar date of 25 October, occurs, according to the Gregorian calendar; on this date, the Bolsheviks storm the Winter Palace.

Name: World War I
Description: 1917   – World War I: The Third Battle of Gaza ends, with British forces capturing Gaza from the Ottoman Empire.

Name: 1918 influenza epidemic
Description: 1918 – The 1918 influenza epidemic spreads to Western Samoa, killing 7,542 (about 20% of the population) by the end of the year.

Name: Kurt Eisner
Description: 1918   – Kurt Eisner overthrows the Wittelsbach dynasty in the Kingdom of Bavaria.

Name: Palmer Raid
Description: 1919 – The first Palmer Raid is conducted on the second anniversary of the Russian Revolution. Over 10,000 suspected communists and anarchists are arrested in 23 U.S. cities.

Name: Patriarch Tikhon of Moscow
Description: 1920 – Patriarch Tikhon of Moscow issues a decree that leads to the formation of the Russian Orthodox Church Outside Russia.

Name: Museum of Modern Art
Description: 1929 – In New York City, the Museum of Modern Art opens to the public.

Name: Chinese Soviet Republic
Description: 1931 – The Chinese Soviet Republic is proclaimed on the anniversary of the October Revolution.

Name: Fiorello H. La Guardia
Description: 1933 – Fiorello H. La Guardia is elected the 99th mayor of New York City.

Name: Spanish Civil War
Description: 1936 – Spanish Civil War: The Madrid Defense Council is formed to coordinate the Defense of Madrid against nationalist forces.

Name: Tacoma, Washington
Description: 1940 – In Tacoma, Washington, the original Tacoma Narrows Bridge collapses in a windstorm, a mere four months after the bridge's completion.

Name: World War II
Description: 1941 – World War II: Soviet hospital ship Armenia is sunk by German planes while evacuating refugees and wounded military and staff of several Crimean hospitals. It is estimated that over 5,000 people died in the sinking.

Name: Richard Sorge
Description: 1944 – Soviet spy Richard Sorge, a half-Russian, half-German World War I veteran, is hanged by his Japanese captors along with 34 of his ring.

Name: Franklin D. Roosevelt
Description: 1944   – Franklin D. Roosevelt is elected for a record fourth term as President of the United States.

Name: Oil Rocks (Neft Daşları)
Description: 1949 – The first oil was taken in Oil Rocks (Neft Daşları), the world's oldest offshore oil platform.

Name: Suez Crisis
Description: 1956 – Suez Crisis: The United Nations General Assembly adopts a resolution calling for the United Kingdom, France and Israel to immediately withdraw their troops from Egypt.

Name: Hungarian Revolution
Description: 1956   – Hungarian Revolution: János Kádár returns to Budapest in a Soviet armored convoy, officially taking office as the next Hungarian leader. By this point, most armed resistance has been defeated.

Name: Cold War
Description: 1957 – Cold War: The Gaither Report calls for more American missiles and fallout shelters.

Name: Carl B. Stokes
Description: 1967 – Carl B. Stokes is elected as Mayor of Cleveland, Ohio, becoming the first African American mayor of a major American city.

Name: Lyndon B. Johnson
Description: 1967   – US President Lyndon B. Johnson signs the Public Broadcasting Act of 1967, establishing the Corporation for Public Broadcasting.

Name: United States presidential election
Description: 1972 – United States presidential election: U.S. President Richard Nixon is re-elected in the largest landslide victory at the time.

Name: United States Congress
Description: 1973 – The United States Congress overrides President Richard Nixon's veto of the War Powers Resolution, which limits presidential power to wage war without congressional approval.

Name: Bangladesh
Description: 1975 – In Bangladesh, a joint force of people and soldiers takes part in an uprising led by Colonel Abu Taher that ousts and kills Brigadier Khaled Mosharraf, freeing the then house-arrested army chief and future president Major General Ziaur Rahman.

Name: Saye Zerbo
Description: 1982 – Colonel Saye Zerbo, president of the military government of Upper Volta, is ousted from power in a coup d'état led by Colonel Gabriel Yoryan Somé.

Name: United States Senate bombing
Description: 1983 – United States Senate bombing: A bomb explodes inside the United States Capitol. No one is injured, but an estimated $250,000 in damage is caused.

Name: Cold War
Description: 1983   – Cold War: The command post exercise Able Archer 83 begins, eventually leading to the Soviet Union to place air units in East Germany and Poland on alert, for fear that NATO was preparing for war

Name: Tunisia
Description: 1987 – In Tunisia, president Habib Bourguiba is overthrown and replaced by Prime Minister Zine El Abidine Ben Ali.

Name: Mass Rapid Transit
Description: 1987   – The Mass Rapid Transit (MRT) system in Singapore opens for passenger service.

Name: Douglas Wilder
Description: 1989 – Douglas Wilder wins the governor's seat in Virginia, becoming the first elected African American governor in the United States.

Name: David Dinkins
Description: 1989   – David Dinkins becomes the first African American to be elected Mayor of New York City.

Name: East German
Description: 1989   – East German Prime Minister Willi Stoph, along with his entire cabinet, is forced to resign after huge anti-government protests.

Name: Mary Robinson
Description: 1990 – Mary Robinson becomes the first woman to be elected President of the Republic of Ireland.

Name: Magic Johnson
Description: 1991 – Magic Johnson announces that he is HIV-positive and retires from the NBA.

Name: WXYC
Description: 1994 – WXYC, the student radio station of the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, launches the world's first internet radio broadcast.

Name: NASA
Description: 1996 – NASA launches the Mars Global Surveyor.

Name: ADC Airlines Flight 086
Description: 1996   – ADC Airlines Flight 086 crashes into the Lagos Lagoon in Epe, Lagos State, Nigeria, killing all 144 people on board.

Name: US presidential election
Description: 2000 – The controversial US presidential election is later resolved in the Bush v. Gore Supreme Court case, electing George W. Bush as the 43rd President of the United States.

Name: Drug Enforcement Administration
Description: 2000   – The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration discovers one of the country's largest LSD labs inside a converted military missile silo in Wamego, Kansas.

Name: Iraq War
Description: 2004 – Iraq War: The interim government of Iraq calls for a 60-day state of emergency as U.S. forces storm the insurgent stronghold of Fallujah.

Name: Jokela school shooting
Description: 2007 – The Jokela school shooting in Jokela, Tuusula, Finland, takes place, resulting in the death of nine people.

Name: earthquake
Description: 2012 – An earthquake off the Pacific coast of Guatemala kills at least 52 people.

Name: Shamshad TV
Description: 2017 – Shamshad TV is attacked by gunmen and suicide bombers, with a security guard killed and 20 people wounded; ISIS claims responsibility for the attack.

Name: Joe Biden
Description: 2020 – Joe Biden is confirmed elected as the 46th president of the United States, defeating incumbent Donald Trump.

Name: António Costa
Description: 2023 – António Costa resigns as Prime Minister of Portugal following news of an investigation in a corruption scandal implicating members of his cabinet.
